<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Functions</title>
  <introduction>
      <p>
          <term>Relations</term> and <term>functions</term> provide a framework for understanding how different groups of items interact with one another. We see relational concepts all the time in the real world, such as the link between <em>an author</em> and <em>a book</em>, or the tie between <em>a citizen</em> and <em>a country</em>. Within mathematics, we rely on similar principles to show how numerical or geometric concepts associate, like stating that one integer is a multiple of another, or recognizing when two shapes are congruent.
      </p>
      <p>
          <term>A function</term> acts as a highly specific type of relation. It establishes a strict rule: for every distinct starting value in an initial group (<term>the domain</term>), there is exactly one guaranteed result in a target group (<term>the codomain</term>). Throughout this chapter, we will examine how these pairings operate across sets, investigate various categories of both relations and functions, and clarify the exact conditions that elevate a standard relation into a true function.
      </p>
      <exploration>
        <title>Relations and Functions</title>
        <interactive xml:id="interactive-relation-vs-function" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/relation-vs-function.js">
